  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Acute Watery Diarrhea (AWD) Prevention and Control Support in Oromia (Shahemene and Boset Woredas) and Tigray (Mekele town) Regions</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Poor social and economic environment, unsafe living conditions associated with insufficient access to safe water supply, inappropriate and poor sanitation and hygiene practices, inadequate food safety &#x2013; including cultural influences on food preparation and storage at home, poor food safety during preparation and storage, inadequate/lack of food safety in markets and restaurants and by street vendors are key aggravating factors of Acute Watery diarrhea (AWD). Reported cases of acute watery diarrhea (AWD) increased since mid-June 2016 as a result of poor hygiene and sanitation practices. Initially reported in Oromia, Somali and SNNP regions, cases were later reported in Addis Ababa on 9 June 2016.  The HRD further indicates that there is a high risk that AWD can spread to all the regions with high speed as there is frequent population movement between Addis Ababa and other regions. 
The overall objective of this project is to support the Government led response to the nationwide outbreak of Acute Watery Diarrhea (AWD) in Oromia and Tigray Regions. The WASH and Health clusters identified key support areas, such as providing water treatment chemicals, NFIs along with hygiene and sanitation promotion activities. This response to AWD will improve access to safe drinking water, improved hygiene and sanitation practices and reduce morbidity and mortality among the vulnerable communities. The targeted project interventions included: Strengthening Surveillance capacity of government health institutions, provision of DDK Kits and water treatment chemicals, Provision of NFIs. Additionally, Hygiene and sanitation promotion and 
 The project will be implemented for six months Tigray (mekele town) and Oromia (shahemene and Boset) regions. The project will directly benefit 818,520 people of the Woreda. This project prioritizes those most vulnerable groups of people, especially children with high degree of vulnerability as primary beneficiaries. In addition, the project is designed to integrate gender throughout the interventions. The project considers the integration of other projects such as quality education for boys and girls, improving household food security, improving health and nutrition status and improved care and participation of children.</narrative>
  </description>
